"1116–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1116":"1116","1225":"1225","1189":"1189","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1160–1189":"1160–1189","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1116–Male":"1116–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1116":"1116","1225":"1225","1189":"1189","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fenwick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern) and Scottish: habitational name from either of two places in Northumberland or from one in Yorkshire, all of which are so named from Old English <i>fenn</i> ‘marsh, fen’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying dairy farm’. There is also a place in Ayrshire, Scotland, which has the same name and origin. This last is the source of at least some early examples of the surname: Nicholaus Fynwyk was provost of Ayr in 1313, and Reginald de Fynwyk or Fynvyk appears as bailie and alderman of the same burgh in 1387 and 1401. The name is usually pronounced ‘Fennick’.","History: The name was brought over from England by several forebears, including George Fenwick (1603–56/7), a colonist from Brinkburn, Northumberland. He was one of the group of lords and gentlemen to whom the earl of Warwick, president of the Council for New England, granted forty leagues of territory west of the Narragansett River. George took up residence with his family at Saybrook, CT, in 1639. John Fenwick of Bynfield, Berkshire, England, established himself at Salem, NJ, in June 1675, the first Quaker settlement on the Delaware."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Baron Robert de Fenwick II was born in 1160, in Matfen, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom as the son of Baron Robert de Fenwick I and Fenwick. He had at least 1 son with Beatrice de Bardolf. He died in 1189, in his hometown, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1160–1189":"1160–1189","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1116–Male":"1116–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1116":"1116","1225":"1225","1189":"1189","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1160–1189":"1160–1189","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1116–Male":"1116–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1116":"1116","1225":"1225","1189":"1189","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1160–1189":"1160–1189","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1116–Male":"1116–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1116":"1116","1225":"1225","1189":"1189","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Baron Robert de Fenwick II est né en 1160, à Matfen, Northumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Baron Robert de Fenwick I et Fenwick. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Beatrice de Bardolf. Il est décédé en 1189, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 29 ans."},"de":{"1160–1189":"1160–1189","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1116–Male":"1116–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1116":"1116","1225":"1225","1189":"1189","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberlandshire, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Fenwick Tower, Matfen, Northumberland, England":"Matfen, Northumberland, England,